toggle : toggle Gravity Drive On/Off

In physics, the inertia of a body, in a Galilean frame of reference (known as inertial), is its tendency to maintain its velocity: in the absence of external influence, any point body persists in a uniform rectilinear motion.
It should be seen as the resistance to the variation in velocity of a body. In rotation, inertia depends on the shape of the object. A good experiment to understand it is to try to make a broom turn. Once in the direction of the axis and once along the length. The first one is very easy and the second one is very hard even though the mass is the same.
A second ultra cool experiment is to spin on a desk chair. By stretching your legs you will slow down and then by curling up your legs together you will speed up 😄
Inertia is related to the concept of "the quantity of motion" p=mv.
Inertia allows you to understand how a bicycle rolls by itself or the notion of a gyroscope.
When you do a somersault you naturally ball up your body to accelerate your rotation speed
In skating it's the same. During hyper rotation the skater brings his body as close as possible to the axis of rotation
The balancer does the opposite. He increases his moment of inertia to facilitate compensation
One last thing. Don't forget that according to Einsteins: E=mc². Otherwise a spinning wheel or a rocket that moves very fast weighs much more than if it was stationary 😉
